deck_excerpt: Start w/ Fiendsmith to set up Wave High King Caesar. Next, Centur-ion Stand and Trudea to get out Primera. Follow up with White Forest combo
deck_description:
Still testing. Super combo. Usually like to start with Fiendsmith Engraver in hand to activate all the way to D/D/D Wave High King Ceaser before Nibiru can be used on you. Then if Centur-ion Stand is in hand, place-discard for cost, set Trudea. Special Trudea, then use its effect to relocate to spell/trap zone & Primera from the deck. Special Primera, on resolution, activate primera to search Wake-up Centur-ion! Place level 8 token, & Synchro using Stand Up (I think, or whatever) into Centur-Ion Legatia. Still haven't normal summoned at this point. If you use Emblema Oath, make sure it's something you're going to use as material (I.e. Primera) or you will be Centur-ion Extra Deck Locked. So from here you can normal summon a White forest monster and that combo begins.You will want to get to Diabel & Silhouhatte Rabbit on the field for a 3-negate trap card that will activate during your opponents turn. In your opponent's turn & if you do not have Crimson Dragon on the field, but you have Diabel, you could use Silvy or Rucia of the White Forest to special summon itself (Shuffeling Rciela back into the Extra deck as cost) during your opponent's turn on to your field, for a disruption. Any special summon will trigger the field spell Stand Up & you could synchro off Diabell & the lvl 4 tuner for a Centur -ion Synchro level 12. But you may want to use Diabel's effect during your opponents turn to special summon Zapper Shrimp from the Extra deck before using the disruptions mentioned above, first. From here you can synchro for Chaos Angel or if you have another lvl 2, synchro for Crimson Dragon. If Crimson Dragon & a lvl 12 synchro monster is on the field while on your oppenents turn, or during turn 2, use it's quick effect to target the lvl12 synchro beast, & synchro summon Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity. Activate it's effect & it's game!

Please comment for suggestions & combos!

*If used lvl 6 tuner synchro monster for Diabel's synchro summon, you can add to your hand 1 spell/trap from the Graveyard. For this situation, I probably had already sent a spell/trap hand trap card, like "Crossout Designator." Add that card back to hand, set before ending the turn. That way I can negate imperm when I plan to activate a monster effect on my opponents turn. I do not want crimson dragon or Hot red Dragon impermed. 

*To get Crimson Dragon out on your opponents turn with Diabel & disruptions during your opponents turn: Diabel quick effect to send spell/trap to special summon Zapper Shrimp. After resolution, since a spell/trap was sent to activate a monster effect, special summon Astellar of the White Forest from the Graveyard. Don't chain Zapper yet since Astellar is not on the board yet. Once on board, use Zapper's quick effect to synchro off for Crimson Dragon using Diabel (lvl 8), Astellar of the White Forest (lvl 2), & Zapper Shrimp (lvl 2 - Tuner). Use Crimson Dragon's quick effect to get out hot red boss during your opponents turn for game!
A deck based on cards Jonouchi used throughout the duelist kingdom manga arc with some additional cards and doubles to reach 40 cards

The turn is usually dependent on the hand, so therefore I cannot outline exact combos. If you have any suggestions, please let me know!

deck_name: A Mecha Fan's Guide to Centur-Ion (July 2024)
deck_excerpt: ATTENTION MECHA FANS, the Centur-Ion ladies have arrived in Masterduel!
deck_description:
ATTENTION MECHA FANS, a new mecha archetype has arrived in Masterduel, and they are none other than Centur-Ions! These ladies combine together with their pilot, machine and spirit partner to synchro summon level 12 boss monsters during your turn and your opponent's turn!
 
Level 12 Synchros are summoned like constantly, leading to the summon of either Legatia (draw 1, destroy 1) or Auxilia (search 1). Both of these mechanical femme fatales generate advantage during the End Phase, placing your spent Centur-Ion starters from the GY and Banished pile in the backrow where they can be used again for next turn. 
 
The hyper consistent nature of Centur-Ions means that this deck can play a whopping 21 staples, meaning you'll always win the "Maxx C" minigame, handtrap your opponent to a standstill, and outgrind your opponent with sheer mechanical might and the power of friendship!
 
YOUR DRILL WILL REACH MASTERS WITH CENTUR-ION! 
 
Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES AND DECKBUILDING
 
The CENTURION deck core is compact because of it's amazing consistency and 1-card starters being only a mere 16 cards. The only Centur-Ion cards that aren't a 1 card starter are Emet VI, Gargoyle II and Phalanx. x2 Bonfire is also another starter since it searches out Trudea. This brings the deck's total to 14 one-card starters, meaning that having them in your opening hand is extremely likely. If you have multiple starters in your hand, you can use them as extenders whenever your opponent interrupts you, so this deck is naturally very resilient to handtraps. 
 
 
STAPLES compose the rest of this deck. 21 staple cards are used because of Centur-Ion's hyper consistency! The usual "Maxx C" package is used, so that the pilot has as much chance to win the Maxx C minigame. Psyframes are used as well, since the deck does many of it's plays without monsters on the field, giving the player ample chances to punish their opponent with Gamma, which in turn can be used to make Omega or Baronne. The 1-of staples are Crossout targets, but in general Nibiru, Imperm, Trust, Talents, Magnumhut, Druiswyrm, etc. are very useful cards as well!
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
Centur-Ion's current main combo is linear, and all cards do the same thing and lead to the same outcome. This means that this deck is extremely predictable, very simple and easy to learn. As said before, most Centur-Ion cards are one card starters, and if your first starter gets interrupted/negated, the other starters in your hand can also act as extenders to continue on your combo. For example, if Primera got impermed/veiler'd, you can summon Primera and continue comboing to get your level 12 synchro boss monster, Legatia. 
 
Since the gameplan hinges the success of the Centur-Ion combo, the pilot must do whatever they can to simplify the opponent's gamestate and bait interruption. Baronne (Horus + Vision Resonator) can be summoned before attempting anything else to insulate your combo lines. Photon Lord can also be made with 2 level 8s (usually 2 Horus monsters) to negate monster effects.
 
Here are Centur-Ion 1-card combo:
 
Primera = Legatia (Pop monster, draw 1 and resource generator) + Calamity Lock (Or Omni-negate with Blazar Dragon) + follow-up 
  1. Normal summon Primera to search Stand-Up! 
  2. Activate Stand-Up! Use Stand-Up's effect to send 1 card from hand to GY to place Trudea on the backrow as a continuous trap. 
  3. Special summon Trudea from the backrow. 
  4. Activate Trudea's effect to place itself on the backrow and Emeth VI from deck on the backrow. 
  5. Special summon Emeth VI from the backrow. 
  6. Synchro summon Legatia using Primera + Emeth VI.
  7. Activate Legatia's on-summon effect to pop a monster with highest ATK your opponent controls (if applicable) and draw 1 card. 
  8. During the End Phase, activate Legatia's effect to place Primera on the backrow as a continuous trap.
  9. During the opponent's Main Phase, special summon Primera (CL1) and Trudea as a level 8 (CL2) from the backrow. 
  10. CL1 Primera to search a Centur-Ion card (usually Bonds since it's excellent follow-up), and CL2 Stand-Up! to synchro summon for Crimson Dragon, CL3 activate Emeth VI in the GY placing Trudea in the backrow. Resolve Stand-Up! Synchro summoning Crimson Dragon using Primera + Emeth VI. 
  11. Activate Crimson Dragon CL1 to search Synchro Rumble from deck, Activate Crimson Dragon CL2 targeting Legatia to synchro summon either Blazar (onmi-negate) or Supernova (banish entire enemy field) from Extra Deck.
With one singular card, you've locked your opponent out of the game, and you have ample follow-up for next turn's OTK! (So unfair, I can feel a King Calamities ban on the horizon).
 
The win condition of Centur-Ion is to outgrind your opponent with immense resource generation with Legatia's +1 draw, Auxila's search, and end phase recursion of Centur-Ion monster cards. If you've slowed down your opponent enough with your handtraps, Supernova and Blazar, you should be able to out-resource your opponent and win!
 
Alternatively if you activated Dimension Shifter, you can still do the above combo, but summon Auxilia instead so you can place Primera in your backrow from Banishment. The best card to search with Auxilia is Stand Up! So you can synchro summon on your opponent's turn, or if you already have it, search for Phalanx instead. 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • If your opponent is targeting your Centur-Ion monster, you can "dodge" their targeting effect if Emeth VI is in your hand or GY! Simply chain Emeth VI's effect to place your monster in the backrow! 
  • Dimension Shifter shuts off many common handtraps that slow down Centur-Ion like Maxx "C", Droll, Ghost Ogre, Ghost Belle and Effect Veiler! If you have the chance, always shotgun your Shifter! 
  • Bystials can trigger Stand Up! By summoning on your opponent's turn, and if Primera/Trudea are on the field, you can synchro summon either Baronne or Chaos Angel! 
  • If your opponent targets your continuous trap card Centur-Ion monster on the backrow during the main phase, you can "dodge" their targeting effect by simply chaining their quick effect summon! 
  • Centur-Ion Phalanx can banish your continuous trap card monsters in the backrow to summon them next stand-by phase. That's because monsters treated as continuous traps in the backrow are still counted as "monsters" and Phalanx reads "target 1 face-up monster card on the field."
  • When choosing either Blazar or Supernova to synchro summon with Crimson Dragon, ask yourself - what counters my opponent more, a omni-negate (Blazar) or field banish (Supernova)? 
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
CONCLUDING REMARKS
 
Centur-Ion's entrance into Masterduel certainly has made waves in higher levels of play! Even though the infamous "Calamity Lock" has been banned recently, Centur-Ion can still consistently win vs. top meta decks because of their extreme consistency, 21 staple cards, and robust gameplan! This mid-range deck many not have as much power as Yubel and Snake-Eyes, but it sure makes up for it with it's reliability on Masterduel ladder! Plus, I personally think mechas and mecha pilots are the coolest thing ever, especially in Yugioh, so this is my new favourite deck for the time being. When the next Centur-Ion support comes out, the deck will surely it'll be good enough to pierce the heavens!
 
GLHF Duelists!

good deck. try it or be sad

This deck doesn't include the Diabellstar package in order to keep its price below $140 side deck included, i'll explain my deckbuilding decisions as follows:

Given that the absence of the Diabellstar Engine represents a heavy hit on consistency, i've decided to use 3 Poplar (1 more than the usual) that can be used both as starters and extenders and 2 Pot of Prosperity (I think 3 would be excessive, besides you could end up drawing 2 of them turn 1).

Following this line, Snake-Eye Birch works pretty fine as a free extender in case of being ashed (the best case scenario because you could link into Hiita and then Promethean from 2 bodies), or being impermed/veiled. I think 2 Snake-Eye Birch are enough.

Zombie Vampire is there just in case you brick into Fire King, you could turn Kirin+Garunix into a Zombie Vampire hoping to mill a Snake-Eye to summon with the same effect, specially useful during mirrors. If you brick into Fire King against a skilled player, you're dead anyways, so by using Zombie Vampire you have the chance of end up on a decent board.

3 Book of Eclipse as a cheap way of boardbreaking, you could use Forbbiden Droplet instead. Both are great options in my opinion.

1 Nibiru as a Crossout Designator target, the 3 Crossouts are necessary for keeping the consistency of the deck without the recursion offered by the Diabellstar package, 2 Original Sinful Spoils instead of 1 are also a necessary evil to not brick or to be able to extend or bridge into Snake Eyes.

Bystial Magnamhut because we're entering into a more diverse format with a lot of Dark/Light monsters, also works as an extender if you're veiled, can be changed for Droll & Lock Bird as a Crossout Designator target.

Circle of Fire King and Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf as great recursion tools. Kikinagashi Fucho to stall a turn against Tenpai in case you have to go first, if you have Snake-Eye Birch on hand you can XYZ summon it easy.

Your desirable end board is: Apollousa 1600ATK (2 monster negations) + Number 38: Hope Harbinger (Spell Negation) + Amblowhale (Recursion tool and Promethean target) with Garunix and Promethean Princess on Graveyard. Number 38 also protects Apollousa from being hit by battle.

Regarding to Side Deck: Every Spell is a boardbreaker tool in case you go second, every Trap is a Win Condition in case you go first. Solemn Judgement is there to protect your field, be careful with the Fire King Island mandatory effect.

Raidraptor deck, aiming to vomit xyz and combo into the big birds, occasionally on the opponent's turn.

If evil enough, it can summon Kali Yuga on the opponent's turn.

deck_excerpt: The Hero Emerges through the darkness to protect the weak.
deck_description:
This is a really fun deck to play with, especially with friends and even on a competitive level. You'll always want to go second with this deck due to the lack of negates this deck has to offer, which is why I added in a few other cards. This deck was inspired by Team Sammurai X1, though I took bits and pieces of what I liked and add other neat things. You won't find many hero decks that are super versatile, so I hope this build stands out.

 

When playing with this deck, I can't help but feel a Jaden Yuki vibe by being able to have Burstinatrix and Avian in your deck, along with the Flame Wingman. Of course, you can always remove that package with something else. However, I found this deck was incredibly consistent. Ash Blossom can be a pain for this deck, which is why I added the three E - Emergency Calls. Not only are they not once per turn, but they'll be a perfect bait, not to mention, resource to build your hand the way you see fit.

 

The main cards for my bread and butter combo are

Vision Hero Farris X3

Vision Hero Increase X2

Vision Hero Vyon X2

Destiny Hero - Malicious X3

Elemental Hero Burstinatrix

Elemental Hero Avian

Evil Hero Adusted Gold

Miracle Fusion

Polymerization

Dark Calling

Xtra Hero Infernal Devicer

Xtra Hero Wonder Driver

Xtra Hero Cross Crusader

Elemental Hero Cosmo Neos

Elemental Hero Sunrise

Elemental Hero Grandmerger

Elemental Hero Flame Wingman

Evil Hero Malicious Bane

 

The Combo will be as followed

- Activate Farris' effect and discard 1 hero from your hand to special summon it to the field

 - Activate Farris' effect and Add Vision Hero Increase to the S/T Zone

- Activate Increases effect and tribute Farris to special summon self to field

- Activate Increases effect and special summon Vylon to the field 

- Acivate Vylon's effect and send Malicious to GY

- Activate Malicious' effect and banish self to special summon Malicious from deck

- Link Malicious and Increase into Devicer

- Activate Devicer's effect and reveal Flame Wingman (Add Burst and Avian to hand)

- Activate Vylon's effect and banish Farris  to add Poly

- Activate Poly to summon Sunrise (Avian and Burstinatrix)

- Activate Sunrise's effect (Add Miracle Fusion)

- Activate Malicious effect and banish self to special summon Malicious from deck

- Link Devicer and and Vylon to summon Wonder Driver

- Activate Miracle fusion to banish Burst and Avian for Grandmerger (Under Wonder)

- Activate Wonder Driver to set Poly

- Link Malicious and Wonder Drive into Cross Crusader

- Activate Cross Crusader's effect and summon Malicious from GY

- Activate Cross Crusader's effect and tribute Malicious to add Adusted Gold

- Discard Adusted Gold to add Dark Calling to hand

- Activate Dark Calling and banish Adusted gold and Farris to summon Bane

 

***If Going second***

- Activate Malicious bane's effect to clear opponent's board

- If a monster can't be destroyed, attack with Grand Merger

- Once a monster is destroyed by Grand Merger, tribute it for Cosmo Neos

- Activate Cosmo Neos' effect to stop foe from using card effects

- OTK and wipe out opponent

 

You have multiple options on getting Farris and one hero to your hand. Now, unfortunately, if you play Fusion Destiny, you are locked out of non-dark attribute monsters. So as an extender, if you find yourself with fusion destiny in your hand after the combo, go ahead and activate it.

 

- Activate Fusion Destiny and send Denier and Plasma to summon Phoenix Enforcer

 

It's just one extra step, Phoenix Enforcer is a pretty sick card, and it really adds on the Aster Phoenix vibe as well. I also went ahead and created a combo that works with just fusion destiny, making it that if for some unknown reason, you can't get your primary combo started, this will be another way to set up your board and obliterate your opponent

 

Combo #2: Dark Lock

- Activate Fusion Destiny (Send Denier and Malicious to grave) summon Phoenix

- Banish Malicious from Grave to special summon Malicious in deck

- Activate Denier and special summon to field and return banished Malicious to deck

- Link Denier and Malicious into Infernal Devicer

- Activate Devier's effect and add Burstinatrix and Avian to hand

- Banish Malicious from grave to special summon Malicious in deck

- Link Phoenix and Malicious to summon Cross Cruesader

- Activate Cross Cruesader to special summon Phoenix to field

- Banish Malicious from grave to special summon Malicious in deck

- Activate Cross Cruesdader and tribute Malicious to add Farris from deck to hand

- Discard Avian and summon Farris

- Activate Farris' effect to add Increase to the S/T zone

- Activate Increase's effect and tribute Farris to special summon Increase

- Activate Increase's effect and special summon Vylon 

- Activate Vylon's effect and send Shadow Mist to grave and add Adusted Gold to hand

- Activate Vylon's effect and banish Shadow Mist and add Poly to hand

- Activate Poly to fuse Vylon and Increase and summon Adoration / Trinity

***If your opponent has a monster that can't be destroyed by effect, summon Trinity

- Activate Adusted Gold and add Dark Calling

- Activate Dark Calling and banish Malicious and Adusted Gold to summon Malicious Bane

 

This combo feels really good and so you have two set ways on playing the deck with this build. Keep in mind, hand traps can be annoying, so be aware of any your opponent might bright. As for your side deck goes, I would add cards that make going first easier, such as your own hand traps, solemn Strike, etc. In other words, you want to be able to stop or at least, limit the boards your opponent makes.

 

I included Mudragon and Starving Venom along with the Super Poly so that way you can break your opponent's board or make some follow up plays. Remember, heroes aren't made for long games, so you'll want to finish off your opponent as quickly as possible. I hope you guys found this deck to be interesting and wish to give it a try. I'll be working on more decks as well that cover certain archetypes such as the Dark Magician, Cyber Dragons, Blue-Eyes, etc.

deck_excerpt: Floowandereeze Going 2nd build. Side deck is to go first. This deck also uses 1 new card from Infinite Forbidden (INFO) set.
deck_description:
Side deck: For the side, I based it on going 1st since the only time your going use it is if you choose to go first game 2 or if you face a tenpai player and they make you go first which is the majority of the time.

Grave of the Ancient Organism ----> Threatening Roar

Lose One Turn -----> Dimensional Barrier 

These side deck changes if your perfer to use Triple Tactics Thrust more when siding or if you feel there is too much back row destruction. Iam just testing the floodgate traps at the moment.

Extra deck: Winter cherries targets(meta dependent) / Ultimate Slayer targets (conflicts with shifter) / Generic XYZ's and Link monsters.

Notes: The new card from the Infinite Forbidden set called Spell card "Soul Exchange" is a very explosive card when breaking boards going 2nd. When mixed with Dimensional Shifter the effect of Soul Exchange, not only are you tributing their monsters but also banishing them from the game. Since the majority of the format is using their extra deck as a second deck, especially in this Fiendsmith meta that we are in currently.

This deck has a lot of diversity and can be played in many ways.

1. #40: try to summon #40 and activate the effect, and use a rank-up spell to pop every other monster on the board, and deal huge damage to the enemy

2. #88 (hard/bad): To pull that off, you want to summon #88 and activate the effect, also banish terror baby in the gy to make 88 invincible to card effects. you might want to switch some cards in the deck like adding swords of revealing lights

3. 1tk: look up a video on youtube on how to do the 1tk, only one card is needed to do so and it works on turn one. add terraforming to make it easier

4. just everything: use everything to make the game as diverse as possible!

Tip: you can revive numbers with perform puppet, if you manage to banish it (its easy with dreary doll!).

 

Good luck and have fun!

deck_excerpt: Zombie swordsmen here to wreck your opponent's day.
deck_description: Ash Blossom serves a dual purpose here as both a hand trap and being able to be used to go into Squiresaga. Squiresaga can banish your zombies to trigger their effects and its own effects. Samuraisaga is mostly just a beatstick - you'll be using it to go into Shogunsaga which will then banish Samuraisaga to go up to 5500 ATK to become a better beatstick. Gold Sarcophagus functions as a searcher that can also trigger Shiranui on-banish effects. Sunsaga can recycle your banished Synchros then pop your opponent's cards. Shiranui Style Samara is very useful for its draw effect, since you can return 2 of your banished zombies (as long as they have 0 defense) to the deck then draw a card - recycling and draw power. It also gets treated as the Shiranui field spell, and some Shiranui cards get better effects when the field spell is up. The actual Field spell isn't being used here, because it's not really that good. Necroface is there for additional banished card recycling.

Majespecters center around tributing their monsters with their Spells and Traps to disrupt your opponent and destroy their board, and they're also very consistent thanks to their massive searching power. After being Tributed, they can come back fairly easily thanks to being Pendulum monsters. Since they're effect monsters, they can be used to go into Exceed The Pendulum to get 3 downward link arrows.

deck_name: WHAT WILL THE CURRENT COMBO KING D/D/D LIKE? THIS IS HOW I USE IT - RANKED SEASON 32
deck_description: The Season 32 of Master Duel Ranked has begun. Today I will start ranked duel with King D/D/D deck. WHAT WILL THE CURRENT COMBO KING D/D/D LIKE? THIS IS HOW I USE IT - RANKED SEASON 32. Below is the deck profile for everyone to refer to.

main goal is to end on:

beatrice

kristya

red-eyes zombie dragon lord

doomking ballerdroch

Zombie World 

+ 2 cards in hand.

Do you like Fusion spam? Me too!

Don't use Dark Law together with the other Masked HEROs, as their effects won't go off due to them requiring cards to be sent to the GY - Dark Law causes your opponent's cards to be banished instead of going to the GY.

Shadow Mist is a critical searcher for the deck. His effect lets you search out a HERO if he's sent to the GY, which is incredibly easy to do thanks to Polymerization, Vision HERO Vyon, and Mask Change. He can also search out a Mask Change if he's special Summoned (such as with Solid Soldier), but you can't use both of those effects on the same turn. If you want to trigger both, you can set Mask Change after you Special Summon him, then use it during your opponent's turn for a Dark Law play to trigger his search effect. I myself usually just use the HERO search effect, though, as I find it more useful.

Blazeman lets you search out Polymerization on summon, but you can also use him to send another Elemental HERO to the GY to become that Attribute. Useful for Mask Change plays. Like Shadow Mist, you can only use one of the effects per turn.

Vision HERO Vyon can send a HERO from the deck to the GY on Summon, so you can use him to proc Shadow Mist's search effect. He can also banish a HERO from the GY to search out Polymerization. The first effect is a hard once per turn, while the second is a soft once per turn. Unlike Shadow Mist and Blazeman, you can use both on the same turn.

For Fusion spam, you're going to want to go into Elemental HERO Sunrise. He can search out Miracle Fusion on summon, which lets you turn him into Wake Up Your Elemental HERO right after that. If you have a Polymerization or another Miracle Fusion, you can summon out another Sunrise or another HERO Fusion.

In most situations, you'll want to use Polymerization before you use Miracle Fusion. Miracle Fusion banishes from the field and GY to Fusion Summon, so you can use the monsters you just sent to the GY with Poly for another Fusion Summon.

Keep in mind that Favorite Contact does not treat the Special Summon as a Fusion Summon.

deck_name: [1st Place] Tam Yee Luk -  Asia Championship 2000
deck_description: That was the 1st place deck by Tam Yee Luk from the Asia Championship 2000. It was held in Tokyo on August 20th, and was the first international tournament. This premiere event was a big deal considering the World Championship was still years away (2003). Tam Yee Luk was from Hong Kong, and won with the Cannon Burn deck; as opposed to a more traditional beatdown strategy. As such, the deck's fan name would be a popular Judo phrase, translated to "Softness overcomes hardness" due to its use of weaker monsters. The deck, as its traditional name alludes to, revolves around Cannon Soldier inflicting burn damage. This is backed up by a consistent rotation of monsters & resources like: Sangan, Magician of Faith, and Ultimate Offering. Comparatively to Good Stuff, this was a bit of a gimmick deck. Also keep in mind that the meta at the time, Deck Destruction was also popular. Since Cyber Jar & Morphing Jar could replenish the hands, this gave an advantage to Tam Yee Luk via more Cannon Soldier fodder. This was a deck built around countermeasures to the meta, even if the deck did have inherent issues such as the large deck size. You could argue that luck, as well as the tournament’s setup had some influence in the outcome, but it certainly took a level of skill to reach the summit.

deck_excerpt: Control deck with a repeatable removal spell in the DMZ
deck_description:
Playing a control deck against 3 other opponent's is pretty hard but if theres anything that could to it it's a combination of eldlich lab and dogmatika. Surely searching and activating sixth sense multiple times will do the trick right? Then try and kill people with Abom and Avram from there

Getting into a bit more detail about the deck our deckmaster Santa Claws acts as a repeatable kaiju, We can use him up to 5 times in a standard game, Santa doesn't really have any synergy with the rest of the deck so if you want depending on your meta you can swap him out with Archfiend Eccentrick who while being worse removal for monsters, is also an MST and is normal summonable if ya wanna make plays with Lyna the Light Charmer, Lustrous or Muckraker From the Underworld

Next up we'll talk about the individual engines inside the deck

Labrynth

Now everyone knows that lab is crazy, but its especially crazy in domain format cause we get to abuse Sixth Sense which will form our decks main engine. Cards like Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle , Labrynth Set-Up , and Farewelcome Labrynth can search it while Lovely Labrynth of the Silver Castle and Redeemable Jar can let us use it repeatedly. We also have Lilith, Lady of Lament which has a chance to search it, make sure to reveal Waking the Dragon as one of the cards for intimidation.

Alongside all the pros above, thanks to the multiplayer nature of the format the battle traps that Labrynth Archfiend can search like cylinder or the mirror forces become really good burn/boardwipes against a mutual enemy, the servants can draw cards, spam the board for extra deck plays, and Arias the Labrynth Butler is a turn 0 play. In addition to all of this Lab synergizes very well with our next engine

Dogmatika

We're not doing much with our extra anyway so why not throw in a dogmatika engine, this also gives us access to Dogmatika Punishment an extremely powerful normal spell for our lab engine, our extra includes a bunch of extremely good sends, Herald of the Arc Light can search Sauravis, the Ancient and Ascended , N'tss and Malong give us extra removal, Omega lets us recycle and Granguignol the Dusk Dragon can summon out Despian Luluwalilith , And maximus can send any 2 of those!

Eldlich

Now finally is our least important engine, most of the reason we're playing them is specifically Eldlich the Golden Lord whos a giant beater that can come back a repeatedly, Cursed Eldland can draw us cards every turn but keep in mind it stops non zombies from attacking, so if you want to make a push youll need to use eldlich's 2nd eff or something to get rid of it, otherwise all the trap monsters become pretty good cards while eldlich is out and if hes not then they can at least be used to make extra deck plays. Silhouhatte Rabbit can search them out and turn them into mst's if you've got spare material around.
I wanted to try to build a deck with a backup boss monster. I think is fun trying to come back to the times where you have 2+ boss monsters in the deck and combine it. Just a fun deck

deck_excerpt: Winged Beasts, Dragons and Synchro Summons
deck_description:
And old deck I made back when Frog Quasar was a top tier deck (last 5D's era sets). This was for casual games, but it was suprinsigly decent against more competitive decks. This deck is very outdated to the point of being unplayable today. Some notes to keep in mind:

  • Blizzard the Far North can summon another copy of itself, what allowed for this deck to use Red Nova Dragon, which would hit the field with at least 5000 ATK. Pair this with the ability Dragunity cards had of bringing level 8 synchro monsters out and this dumb combo is more or less worth the deck space.
  • Dragunity at the time would use Stardust Assault Mode. Because of the Blackwing engine, there is no space in the main deck for it, but I would side it if I felt like I needed.
  • Dark Simorgh and Stardust combined would be more than enough protection against most forms of removal the opponent had.
  • Super Polymerization was there along with Doppelwarrior and Dragon Knight Draco-Equiste to counter Shooting Quasar Dragon. Draco-Equiste then could use Quasar's effect against the opponent. This strategy worked against Stardust Dragon and Trishula too. A specific albeit dumb for the time strategy that worked more times than it should have. Doppelwarrior was the warrior monster of choice because it would synergize with the deck's main strategy on its own, preventing it from becoming a dead draw.
  • Kalut the Moon Shadow was there to guarantee Shura the Blue Flame could proc its effect, searching for Gale the Whirlwing, what lead to Blackwing Armor Master.
  • Dragunity Aklys serves as extra fodder for Cards of Consconance along with Phalanx, and the paired with Dragunity Legionnaire would become a complementary form of removal.
  • Zephyros the Elite can be realiably used to reset Dragon Ravine, Dragunity Dux, Dragunity Legionnaire, Blizzard the Far North and Gale the Whirlwind. It also allowed Dragunity Legionnaire to be used to summon Dragunity Knight - Vajrayanna.
Master duel exosister deck with vaal engine support
